erage is generated from the java agent, and there might be API signature changes if we're calling a superclass method. I’m considering whether the native provider setup caused issues with the AES SecretKeyFactory as well.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing BouncyCastle issues**\\n\\nI’m digging into the BouncyCastleProvider constructor, which loads algorithm mappings dynamically. It seems that in the native context, the necessary metadata is missing, leading to absent algorithms. I wonder if directly configuring AES.Mappings could help. Instantiating ConfigurableProvider doesn’t seem viable. I’m also considering whether the coverage tool excludes calls from test subclasses, particularly with ExposedAesKeyFactory. It might be worthwhile to examine the dynamic access agent output for any relevant calls.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_svLrogLwxirN8Fk37SPVr84Y|fc_07682197761587bf016a25efc2f1d08196a4016d7f8d132540", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bcprov-jdk15to18/1.77/build/native/agent-output -type f -maxdepth 5 -print | sort | xargs -r grep -n \"BaseSecretKeyFactory\\|RawEncodedKeySpec\\|X509EncodedKeySpec\" | head -100", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1092, "output": 563, "cacheRead": 45056, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 46711, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780871092708, "responseId": "resp_07682197761587bf016a25efb577bc8196a13bae0b4cbbd66f"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_svLrogLwxirN8Fk37SPVr84Y|fc_07682197761587bf016a25efc2f1d08196a4016d7f8d132540", "toolName": "bash", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "(no output)"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1780871107393}]}
